CHANGES to PARENT TEACHER CONFERENCES NEXT WEEK:
In an effort to limit the number of people in buildings on one day, we will be spreading PT Conferences out over 3 days: Monday, Tuesday and Thursday 3:30-5:30pm.
As usual, Elementary Conferences will be by appointment, and MS/HS will be Drop Ins on any of the three days.
For our working parents who do not get off work in time: please contact your child's teacher to set up a time to conference via Zoom or telephone.
If you have any questions, please contact your building principals.

Join us for our first pep rally of the year! It will be an outside pep rally. Students will be spaced out in the field by grade level. **PLEASE NOTE**
Parents who plan to attend, we ask that you do not park in the concrete lot where the old middle school used to be. Please do not park in the HS Student Parking Lot or in the Middle School Parking Lot either. we ask that you please park on the street on Blakely, at the football field lot, or on the west side of the gym.

There will be kids walking through campus and we want to keep everyone safe!

FROM THE SUPERINTENDENT:
We've had a great first week of school. I would like to give a shout out to all the parents/guardians, faculty and staff, and students for taking the responsibility of our collective school health seriously and for the willingness to adapt to all the changes that had to be made for this school year. It is truly refreshing to witness everyone on the same page doing what has to be done so that we can continue to offer in-person instruction.
Thank you again for your patience, understanding, and most of all your grace in this unprecedented time.
Mr. Burch

FOR TOMORROW'S SCRIMMAGE:
We are looking forward to seeing our team on the field again! In order to ensure player and fan safety and health so that we can continue play uninterrupted this season, we are asking several things of our Redskin fans:
1. We encourage fans to practice physical distancing with families sitting together.
2. Fans are welcome to bring lawn chairs and space out sitting on the track.
3. No chairs on the grass inside the oval track. (i.e. any of the grass on the playing field and surrounding perimeter).
4. Masks are recommended if you cannot physically distance.
5. We highly recommend and encourage no gathering on the field at the conclusion of the scrimmage.
#whynot
#unstoppable

NEW MORNING PROCEDURES
1. Elementary Students will no longer meet in the Cafeteria before school.
2. All PreK-3rd Grade Students should be dropped off at the main entrance to the Elementary on Choctaw.
3. All 4th/5th Graders should be dropped off at the East Vault Entrance on 7th Street.
4. 1st-5th Grade Students will eat breakfast in their classrooms from 7:30-7:55am. PreK and K will eat breakfast in the cafeteria at 8am.
5. MS and HS Students will eat breakfast at their normal time after 1st hour.
BREAKFAST IS FREE FOR ALL STUDENTS.
Afternoon pick up procedures remain the same as last year.
PLEASE NOTE: THE GATE AT 7TH AND CHOCTAW WILL BE CLOSED FROM 7AM-330PM AND THERE IS NO THROUGH ACCESS.

PARENT TECHNOLOGY SCHOOL
Learn how to use, navigate and monitor the apps, devices and programs your children will be using in their classrooms this year.
Parents will choose the training sessions they want to attend.

Each of the classes will take place @ 6:00, 6:30, 7:00pm.
1. IXL, Mastery Connect and Study Island
2. Wengage (Monitoring Student Grades) and School Website (subscribing to District Calendar, online payments for cafeteria etc).
3. Google Classroom/Google Meets
4. Google Suite (Docs, Forms, Sheets, and Slides)
Classes will be 25 minutes each

Classes will be taught by Rush Springs teachers and administrators. Bring a device if you have one. A limited number of devices will be available for parents to use while in the training.
Please fill out the google form if you are planning to attend.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLScwwXViW5exDNZp1x0yHxsnQviM-YDOI7fg-icWo6VWpS3z9A/viewform?usp=sf_link

That's a wrap on Summer Pride 2020. These young men and women showed resiliency and flexibility in the face of an ever changing situation and it will make all the difference in their individual sports. I'm proud of the coaches who helped this summer make this happen. It wasn't easy and required more effort to help our kids get better and make up ground coming out of quarantine. I don't buy into the negativity, I'm excited to see what these young men and women do this school year. We've started to adopt the fight and mentality of not being victims. We don't GET TO play or HAVE TO play anyone. They HAVE TO PLAY US! It's not longer why us? It's #WHYNOT us? Great summer, Redskins! Let's get after it! #rUShvseverybody #EAT #EarnIt

Today we would have celebrated Kenzie girls birthday! She would have been 18 years old! Kenzie was kind and sweet and absolutely hilarious! She loved people well! She saw everyone and was a true light to this world!

Four years ago we started a scholarship in her memory! This scholarship is awarded to a Rush Springs Senior each year. This scholarship has nothing to do with academic or athletic achievements, this scholarship is all based on character; the kind of character that makes a difference! This scholarship is awarded to a student who sees those kids others don‚Äôt, who is kind, compassionate, and a light in their hallways and community!

It is with great privilege and honor, today on Kenzie‚Äôs bday, that we announce our 2020 recipient for The Difference Maker scholarship... Caleb Heston!

This scholarship is made possible by those of you who participate in our Blessing T program! Thank you for being a blessing! ‚ù§Ô∏è üëï #makeadifference #scholarships #blessingt #teamwingts

post_text:
The deadline for OKLAHOMA'S PROMISE APPLICATIONS (8th, 9th, and 10th grade students)is nearing: JUNE 30, 2020! This is the last opportunity for students who just finished the 10th grade to apply. For more information about Oklahoma's Promise visit https://www.okhighered.org/okpromise/

SPECIAL NOTICE TO PARENTS: If your student is or was in the 10th grade during the 2019-20 school year and you anticipate that your 2020 income may be under the $55,000 application limit for the Oklahoma‚Äôs Promise scholarship due to recent reductions in your income, you may submit an application based on your 2020 estimated income. The application must be submitted prior to the June 30, 2020, deadline. You will be required to provide a copy of your 2020 federal tax return when completed to verify that your 2020 income was under $55,000. The application will be held as pending until the tax documentation is received. Please send any questions to okpromise@osrhe.edu.

Oklahoma‚Äôs Promise: ALERT for 10th-Grade Parents with Recent Income Loss

https://www.okhighered.org/okpromise/

If your student is or was in the 10th grade during the 2019-20 school year and you anticipate that your 2020 income may be under the $55,000 application limit for the Oklahoma‚Äôs Promise scholarship due to recent reductions in your income, you may submit an application based on your 2020 estimated income. The application must be submitted prior to the June 30, 2020 deadline at https://secure.okcollegestart.org/applications/Oklahoma_Promise/apply.html?application_id=3544.
You will be required to provide a copy of your 2020 federal tax return when completed to verify that your 2020 income was under $55,000. The application will be held as pending until the tax documentation is received. Please send any questions to okpromise@osrhe.edu.

Due to distance learning and social distancing requirements, this year‚Äôs student council election will be done digitally. Packets will be emailed to applicants and the election will be done across the student body through Google Forms. Applications will be accepted through May 8th. Election forms will be sent out on May 11th and new members announced on May 13th.

If you are a current Junior, Sophomore, Freshman, or 8th grader who will be an incoming Freshman next school year and you are interested in running for a student council position, please contact Ashlie White at awhite@rushsprings.k12.ok.us for an application packet.

Joleen Chaney
April 14 at 5:16 PM ¬∑

Screen grab from Monday‚Äôs 10pm newscast. I‚Äôm reading a script about a metro school district controversy over providing meals to students during this pandemic. A couple of weeks ago, the food service that provides meals to my hometown school district contacted me. They told me Rush Springs Schools has been providing meals to so many students each day, and that without this continued service provided by the school, many children wouldn‚Äôt have much food if any at all. It is a great undertaking and quite impressive for such a small district. They asked me if I‚Äôd like to volunteer. I‚Äôm honored to make the drive home Wednesday morning to the same campus where I had school lunches each day as a kid. Proud our little community is always looking out for each other‚Äôs children, because at one time...I was one of them. ‚ù§Ô∏è

We have compiled a list of free resources for parents and students to use at home during the mandatory school closure. It includes all subjects and grade levels. There are printable worksheets, digital worksheets, videos, projects, experiments and much more. Please use the link below. The link can also be found on the home page of our school website.

We know that accessing this material requires data plans/internet. If you are unable to access the internet, spelling, vocabulary, reading, writing/journaling, arts and crafts and building projects (blocks, legos etc) are all excellent ways to help kids exercise their brains during this mandatory closure period.

Link to Educational Resources:
https://s3.amazonaws.com/scschoolfiles/57/educational_resources_for_parents_for_website.pdf

Well, we arrived this morning hoping to punch a few tickets to State, but we fell short. Couldn‚Äôt be more proud of this group over the past month, grinding and competing to get better. They are laying the foundation for the future of Rush Springs Athletics, and now it‚Äôs time to take this new strength and turn it in to explosive power on the track, diamond, field, and court.

We still set several PR‚Äôs today!

Deadlift
Kenton Jones 290 (+15)
Kade Worden 385 (+20)
Haygon Jennings 260 (+15)
Caden Moore 425 (+20)
Matthew Aucoin 235 (+10)

Squat
Collier Ladwig 290 (+15)
Haygon Jennings 235 (+5)
Caden Moore 340 (+10)
Trevor Heath 270 (+5)

We still have one more meet on Monday with our girls headed to girls state in Dickson!

Every day is a great day to be a Redskin!

#EAT #LiftHeavy #rUShvseverybody

All students received information for their parents to visit the Scholastic website with our school information to shop online as well as information to set up an Ewallet account. Many parents have already set up Ewallet accounts and deposited money for their child.

Please contact Mrs. Jordan with any questions.

Crosslight Amanda Scott shared a link to the group: Crosslight Photography.
February 6 at 10:02 AM ¬∑

It has taken 2 full nights of uploading (country wifi does not like winter weather in case you were wondering) but I finally have the Lil Skins action shots from last weekend in a gallery. You can purchase action shots through the link below. They're 2.00 per image and the download will be sent directly to you once the purchase is complete. And don't forget I love tag backs on the social media ;)

Also just a reminder: we'll be doing half of the Lil Skins team photos this Saturday the 8th and the other half Thursday the 13th and I can't wait!!! <3

It's so exciting to see this program grow each year.
Good luck at Regionals!

post_text:
Social Media can be a great thing when used responsibly but like all things, there are definite hazards to it, especially with our young people. Check out these resources put together by National Online Safety. Knowledge is power!
#CantStopWontStop
shared_text:
Jackson County Comprehensive High School
January 22 at 7:33 PM ¬∑

National Online Safety has put together some fantastic resources for parents about social media apps, online games, and trending issues so they can have informed discussions with their children. THESE ARE PICTURES OF THE DOCUMENTS to give you an idea of what's available/discussed.

All resources, plus much more, can be accessed from the National Online Safety website: https://nationalonlinesafety.com/resources/wake-up-wednesday/
You can register for free and get a weekly update.

You can download some of the resources from a Google Drive folder: http://bit.ly/2v8rsEX (additional resources available from National Online Safety website, )

Visit the National Online Safety Facebook page: https://www.facebook.com/NationalOnlineSafety/
